26:41.934 --> 26:50.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now to questions
surrounding a
significant advance in
reproductive technology

26:50.309 --> 26:52.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with DNA and embryos.

26:52.444 --> 26:57.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The change on the horizon was
pioneered and
approved in England and it is
now being considered

26:57.149 --> 27:02.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for use in the U.S. Proponents
believe it
may eliminate dangerous disease
in children,

27:02.888 --> 27:05.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but others have raised ethical
concerns.

27:05.424 --> 27:10.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, the National Academy of
Sciences recommended
that clinical trials go forward
in the U.S.

27:11.063 --> 27:12.865 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has our look.

27:12.965 --> 27:17.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This new
technology is called
mitochondrial replacement
technique, or MRT

27:17.870 --> 27:19.605 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for shot.

27:19.705 --> 27:23.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mitochondria are tiny structures
that exist
in nearly all the cells in our
bodies, and

27:23.108 --> 27:27.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have their own unique DNA. The
problem is,
a very small number of women
have defective

27:27.813 --> 27:32.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mitochondria, and if they have
children, those
kids inherit their mom's
mitochondria and

27:32.918 --> 27:37.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can suffer terrible, sometimes
fatal, problems,
including brain damage and heart
failure.

27:37.756 --> 27:42.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This new technology would, in
essence, replace
that original mitochondria in
either the mother's

27:42.494 --> 27:47.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
egg or in the parents' embryo
with healthy
mitochondria from a third
person. A child

27:47.766 --> 27:51.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
born this way would then be
carrying the DNA
of three different people.

27:51.503 --> 27:56.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier today, patient advocate
Laurie Strongin
told us why the advance was so
important for

27:56.475 --> 27:58.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a small group of parents.

27:58.277 --> 28:01.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LAURIE STRONGIN, Patient
Advocate: One of
the things that we have found is
that parents'

28:01.413 --> 28:09.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
desire to have genetically
related offspring
is a widely held desire. It's
not universal,

28:09.388 --> 28:11.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but it's widely held.

28:11.690 --> 28:23.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the potential to use MRT to
have offspring
who are genetically related to
both parents

28:23.335 --> 28:30.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is something that families who
carry mtDNA
disease really want. And not
everyone is going

28:30.642 --> 28:37.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to pursue it, but for the family
for whom
having children who are -- who
have a nuclear

28:37.249 --> 28:42.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
genetic connection to them, this
is something
that will just be one of
numerous options

28:42.955 --> 28:44.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
available to them.

28:44.823 --> 28:48.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Joining me now
to discuss
the technology and its
implications are Johns

28:48.393 --> 28:52.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hopkins bioethics Professor
Jeffrey Kahn,
who chairs the panel at the
National Academy

28:52.798 --> 28:57.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Medicine that recommended
moving forward
with the technology, and Marcy
Darnovsky,

28:57.903 --> 29:01.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who writes widely on these
issues and is the
executive director of the Center
for Genetics

29:01.807 --> 29:02.975 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Society.

29:03.075 --> 29:04.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Jeffrey Kahn, I would like
to start with
you.

29:04.943 --> 29:09.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I wonder if you could just tell
us a little
bit more about this technology.
To my ear,

29:09.281 --> 29:14.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this sounds like what we know of
as some sort
of modified version of in vitro
fertilization.

29:14.119 --> 29:16.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you tell us a little bit
more? What is
this technology?

29:16.922 --> 29:18.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY KAHN, Johns Hopkins
University: Yes.

29:18.857 --> 29:23.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is, in fact, a modified
version of in vitro
fertilization, as you noted.
However, it's

29:23.829 --> 29:30.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
picking up the nuclear DNA, the
DNA that we
think of as creating the traits
that make

29:30.369 --> 29:34.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us who we are, and picking that
up and putting
it into a healthy environment of
mitochondria.

29:34.473 --> 29:40.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you noted in the intro, there
are women
who suffer from mutations in
addition those

29:40.479 --> 29:45.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mitochondrial DNA that will
cause really terrible
diseases in their offspring. So,
this is a

29:45.217 --> 29:51.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way to avoid that and preserve
the genetic
relationship. The difference, or
the challenges,

29:51.523 --> 29:54.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this has never before been done
in a human.

29:54.426 --> 30:01.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the FDA, which is charged
with regulating
license applications in new
areas like this,

30:01.600 --> 30:06.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asked the National Academy of
Medicine to
hold the consensus committee to
evaluate the

30:06.672 --> 30:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ethics, social, and policy
issues related
to this technology.

30:10.575 --> 30:12.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the report that was
released today.

30:12.344 --> 30:15.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, just so --
I know there
are some viewers who are
wondering. We're

30:15.947 --> 30:21.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not talking about tweaking the
DNA that affects
our hair color or our
intelligence or things

30:21.119 --> 30:21.820 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like that.

30:21.920 --> 30:23.622 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY KAHN: No, that's right.

30:23.722 --> 30:26.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the mitochondria actually
are quite
important. Otherwise, there
wouldn't be this

30:26.892 --> 30:32.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
need, because people who have
defective mitochondria
have terrible disease issues.
So, mitochondria

30:32.631 --> 30:37.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
create energy for every cell in
our body.
And they also have some other
implications

30:37.369 --> 30:39.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the cellular development
level.

30:39.638 --> 30:45.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, no, it isn't actually a
way to change
the things we think of as making
us who we

30:45.610 --> 30:50.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are, eye color, hair color. You
mentioned
intelligence, athletic ability,
all the kinds

30:50.649 --> 30:55.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of things we might think of in
the so-called
designer baby problems. It
wouldn't do that.

30:55.253 --> 30:59.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really picking up a healthy
population
of mitochondria and replacing
that for those

30:59.124 --> 31:05.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are diseased, and a way
forward which
we think we have crafted which
allows a responsible,

31:05.931 --> 31:12.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ethically acceptable way
forward, but with
great precaution and numerous
restrictions.

31:12.571 --> 31:16.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I'm just
curious. We mentioned
this is a relatively small
number of people

31:16.208 --> 31:17.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who would use this. How many
people are we
talking about?

31:17.976 --> 31:22.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY KAHN: In the hundreds of
people, so
not -- across the entire
country. And part

31:22.948 --> 31:25.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of that is because it's a very
homogeneous
disease.

31:25.884 --> 31:31.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really hard to detect and
diagnose, and
only a small number of people
have a severe

31:31.656 --> 31:35.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough version that we know for
sure that
they're going to pass it on and
that the children

31:35.360 --> 31:41.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are born will be affected.
That said,
they very desperately want to
have a way to

31:41.133 --> 31:43.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have children who are related to
them.

31:43.235 --> 31:49.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The alternative for those
individuals, otherwise,
is adoption, not having
children, or egg donation.

31:49.207 --> 31:53.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is a different thing
for those individuals.
And it's an area we thought
needed to be respected

31:53.678 --> 31:55.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the part of people who wanted
it.

31:55.213 --> 31:57.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Marcy Darnovsky,
I want to turn to you.

31:57.716 --> 32:01.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know you have some concerns
