with your mouth.

45:05.202 --> 45:11.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The baby's lungs
fill with
air, and a cry echoes through
the operating

45:11.208 --> 45:21.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
room. The lives of both mother
and child are
saved, just as the lights come
back on.

45:22.019 --> 45:28.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last week, a year-and-a-half on,
we received
this photo of Muna's baby,
Malishka (ph).

45:28.125 --> 45:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She may soon have a sibling, as
Muna is pregnant
again. There are no numbers that
can adequately

45:36.567 --> 45:43.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
convey the value of this
hospital, in this
place, for this family.

45:43.174 --> 45:50.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour."

45:50.715 --> 45:58.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the
"NewsHour" Bookshelf.

45:59.090 --> 46:04.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I recently sat down with Jay
Newton-Small.
She is a Washington
correspondent for "TIME,"

46:04.662 --> 46:12.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
magazine and she's author of
"Broad Influence:
How Women Are Changing the Way
America Works."

46:12.169 --> 46:13.971 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jay Newton-Small, welcome.

46:14.071 --> 46:14.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL, Author, "Broad
Influence:
How Women Are Changing the Way
America Works":

46:14.605 --> 46:16.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thanks so much.

46:16.307 --> 46:18.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I guess there's
no confusing
what broad refers to here,
right?

46:18.342 --> 46:20.177 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:20.277 --> 46:22.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: No. It's
actually referring
to women. And I don't know if
you knew this,

46:22.279 --> 46:26.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but broad used to be a pretty
derogatory term
for women, which we're hoping to
sort of reclaim

46:26.851 --> 46:31.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it a little bit, but it used to
apply to our
hips, because we have broad
hips, because

46:31.522 --> 46:32.857 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we bear children.

46:32.957 --> 46:34.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And of course we bear children.
We should
be proud of that fact.

46:34.859 --> 46:38.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I
absolutely remember
when it was considered a
derogatory term.

46:38.629 --> 46:40.398 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But times are changing.

46:40.498 --> 46:45.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jay Newton-Small, you do a lot
of reporting
here on how women are doing.
What's really

46:45.636 --> 46:51.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
interesting, though, is how you
document women
have to reach a certain level, a
critical

46:51.676 --> 46:56.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mass, so to speak, before things
really change.
And you reported on the U.S.
Congress. Talk

46:56.781 --> 46:57.948 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about that and what you found.

46:58.049 --> 46:59.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: Sure.

46:59.917 --> 47:03.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the book actually grew from
a story that
I did for "TIME" magazine about
two years

47:03.421 --> 47:08.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ago during the government
shutdown, where
the 20 women at that point of
the 100-member

47:08.759 --> 47:13.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. Senate got together and
restarted the
negotiations to reopen the
government, when

47:13.597 --> 47:15.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
none of the men would talk to
each other.

47:15.633 --> 47:21.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that -- I really was
interested in that
session, because those 20 women
ended up producing

47:21.405 --> 47:25.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more than 75 percent of the
major legislation
that passed that session. They
really batted

47:25.376 --> 47:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
well above they are weight. And
I got -- it
turns out there's this theory of
critical

47:31.382 --> 47:33.250 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mass.

47:33.350 --> 47:37.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, somewhere between 20 percent
and 30 percent,
women really begin to change an
institution,

47:37.121 --> 47:41.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whether it's a legislature or a
corporate
board, a Navy ship or an
appellate court.

47:41.726 --> 47:45.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then I started looking at
all those corners
and finding other areas where
women had reached

47:45.629 --> 47:49.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this sort of tipping point, and
they were
really beginning to change the
way we govern,

47:49.300 --> 47:51.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
change the way we manage, change
the way we
command.

47:51.435 --> 47:55.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What is it about
the 20 or
30 percent? Why isn't it 50
percent?

47:55.706 --> 48:00.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: So, it's
interesting. You
know, one woman really is a
token. Two or

48:00.678 --> 48:05.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
20 percent -- or, like, sort of
less than
20 percent are considered kind
of a pair.

48:05.282 --> 48:08.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's -- there have been a
ton of studies
that show -- or at least two
studies that

48:08.552 --> 48:12.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can think of that show that
pairs are actually
worse than either having one or
three, because

48:12.590 --> 48:17.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
either the women are considered
conspiratorial
or they're considered sort of
archenemies.

48:17.762 --> 48:20.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's this strange kind of, I
don't know
what's going on with the two.

48:20.965 --> 48:24.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when you start getting a
plurality of
the women, three or more,
depending on the

48:25.069 --> 48:30.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
size of the institution, that's
when you really
begin -- women's voices are
considered less

48:30.541 --> 48:33.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exceptional, and it's not this
weird thing,
like, where are you coming from?
And it becomes

48:34.011 --> 48:38.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
less -- sort of less
objectifying them, and
more sort of normal, like
brother and sister

48:38.115 --> 48:39.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or normal work areas.

48:39.984 --> 48:44.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what did you
find that
women want to do differently
from men? Where

48:44.922 --> 48:50.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
does the policy change or the
direction of
an organization change because
of women who

48:50.995 --> 48:52.029 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are making decisions?

48:52.129 --> 48:54.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: It depends on
the organization.

48:54.431 --> 48:58.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there's been a lot of great
research,
one that shows that women tend
to be a lot

48:58.202 --> 49:01.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more prepared than men. They
tend to really
want to dig in on an issue.
Women ask the

49:02.006 --> 49:07.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hard questions and say, where's
the accounting?
Where's the money going? How is
it being spent?

49:07.678 --> 49:11.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Women also tend to be more
collaborative.
They tend to look for win-win
situations,

49:11.949 --> 49:17.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
where everybody can win,
everyone can advance
together, whereas men can be --
not all men,

49:17.421 --> 49:21.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but a lot of men can be sort of
zero-sum game,
I win, you lose.

49:21.425 --> 49:24.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, those are two sort of very
common aspects
of...

49:24.361 --> 49:26.096 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

49:26.197 --> 49:28.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But it's not as
if all women
agree on the direction things
should go.

49:28.265 --> 49:30.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: No, and -- not
at all.

49:30.201 --> 49:34.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, you see that in
the Senate.
For example, you had Senator
Kirsten Gillibrand

49:34.839 --> 49:39.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from New York and Claire
McCaskill from Missouri
disagreeing over how to do
sexual assault

49:39.677 --> 49:41.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the military bill.

49:41.579 --> 49:45.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that is the great joy of
having enough
women to disagree. Right? You
don't have to

49:45.516 --> 49:49.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all be on the same page to go
places. But
what you have to do is respect
each other.

49:49.320 --> 49:53.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, so, notably, when they
disagreed, they
agreed not to recriminate each
other, not

49:53.457 --> 49:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to like sling accusations or
insults. They
just said, we disagree, but we
still appreciate

49:59.797 --> 50:01.599 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
each other's perspectives.

50:01.699 --> 50:04.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was struck that
the one area
where you said there doesn't
seem to be change

50:04.735 --> 50:08.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when they get to critical mass
is the private
sector. And you looked at the
financial industry.

50:08.672 --> 50:12.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there was a quote from a
woman who had
been on several corporate
boards. She said:

50:13.077 --> 50:19.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"There's a trend. When women and
money penetrate
a sector, the money and power
leaves it."

50:19.550 --> 50:23.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She said: "When women finally
got into investment
banking, all the money went to
private equity.

50:23.320 --> 50:27.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When women got into private
equity, it went
to hedge funds."

50:27.124 --> 50:29.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, why is it different?

50:29.560 --> 50:33.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: I don't know
that it's the
men are -- I can't say that
they're, like,

50:33.764 --> 50:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conspiring -- conspiring to keep
women out
of it.

50:36.834 --> 50:42.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what -- it is the sense
that, when you
are diversifying, when the power
structure

50:42.873 --> 50:47.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is no longer the people that
look exactly
like you, it moves beyond the
sort of core

50:47.678 --> 50:52.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
group of a certain number of
people, that
that makes some people
uncomfortable. It makes

50:52.750 --> 50:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many -- certain people leave,
start different
industries, start to do
different things.

50:58.055 --> 51:01.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Women are chasing the money,
but, to some
degree -- like, you see this
also in medicine,

51:01.525 --> 51:05.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for example. When women weren't
allowed into
medicine, and then they were
finally allowed

51:05.296 --> 51:09.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into pediatrics, right, and all
the, like,
money left pediatrics. And then
women were

51:09.199 --> 51:12.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
finally allowed into some kind
of surgery,
but the kinds of surgery they're
in are not

51:12.636 --> 51:14.405 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the kinds that all the money is
made.

51:14.505 --> 51:18.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it is striking. It's an
interesting
phenomenon. And I don't know
what that says

51:19.076 --> 51:20.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about our culture.

51:20.344 --> 51:23.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But it raises
some interesting
questions.

51:23.380 --> 51:28.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Finally, Jay Newton-Small, you
say you're
hopeful about the future. Why?

51:28.152 --> 51:32.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: Well, so, it
was economic
necessity that first brought
women into the

51:32.523 --> 51:35.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
work force with Rosie the
Riveter during World
War II.

51:35.759 --> 51:39.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it wasn't until 1970 that
all of the laws
banning married women from
working without

51:39.897 --> 51:44.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their husband's permission were
fully repealed.
And I think it will be economic
necessity

51:44.268 --> 51:48.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that brings women to the work
force now, fully.
And you see that. We're right on
the cusp

51:48.305 --> 51:53.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of it. So, by 2030, the baby
boomer generation
will fully retire and we will be
short 26

51:53.944 --> 51:55.779 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
million workers.

51:55.879 --> 51:58.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's only two ways to make up
that shortfall.
One, you bring in a ton of new
immigrants,

51:58.382 --> 52:02.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is really hard to imagine
with this
Congress. Or, two, you bring
women up to full

52:02.586 --> 52:06.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
employment. And that is a lot
easier -- much
more easily done. There's plenty
of qualified

52:06.957 --> 52:10.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
women who can do it. We make up
more than
half of the college degrees
already. And so

52:10.961 --> 52:12.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it will be easy to -- much
easier to do that.

52:12.963 --> 52:15.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's 15
years away, but
maybe things will change in the
meantime.

52:16.033 --> 52:17.434 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: I'm betting on
it.

52:17.534 --> 52:18.202 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

52:18.302 --> 52:19.203 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jay Newton-Small.

52:19.303 --> 52:21.739 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The book is "Broad Influence."

52:21.839 --> 52:23.741 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you very much.

52:23.841 --> 52:31.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAY NEWTON-SMALL: Thank you,
